g.text: TOWARDS THE NEXT GENERATION OF AIR MONITORING

text.tspan: Responsible for an estimated 3.4 million deaths
annually, outdoor air pollution is perhaps the
world’s deadliest environmental problem. At the
same time, it’s the most widespread. It affects
everyone, regardless of geography or social
status.
In the United States alone, air pollution accounts for
around 200,000 premature deaths a year. That's six
times the number of people killed in car accidents.
What can we do to better understand the risks air
pollution poses to human health and ecosystems?
To answer this question, the Yale Environmental
Performance Index convened scientists from
around the world to identify existing gaps in the
measurement of four air pollutants: ozone,
particulate matter, persistent organic pollutants,
and mercury. We asked these experts to identify
needed investments for the design of ‘next
generation’ air indicators to inform policy action.
Here is what they came up with - illustrated and
animated by a team of students at Yale University.
Click on each of the sections to explore:
• what each pollutant is and where it comes from
• how its measured
• what is needed to advance new indicators.
Mercury travels long distances
through the air and affects human
health by accumulating in food
chains through the oceans.
Transported through air, POPs are
highly toxic chemicals found in
agriculture, industry, and some
household products.
Particulate Matter is a general term
referring to pollutants that originate
from a broad range of sources and
have damaging health effects.
Ozone - known for being ‘good up
high, bad nearby’ - has negative
impacts on human health, air
quality and climate change.
